properties.headline: Special Weather Statement issued April 15 at 3:30AM EDT by NWS Burlington VT
properties.description:
...Please check with state and local authorities regarding
guidelines for allowed activities...

* Very warm air temperatures in the mid 70s to low 80s are expected
this weekend. This may cause people to underestimate the dangers of
the cold water temperatures which are currently only in the upper
30s to mid 40s across Lake Champlain, and in the 30s and 40s in the
regions' smaller lakes and rivers.

* The cold water temperatures can quickly cause hypothermia to
anyone immersed in the water. According to the US Coast Guard,
when the water temperatures are below 50 degrees, the chance of
immediate incapacitation due to cold shock is extremely high.
Anyone on small boats, canoes or kayaks should plan accordingly
if recreating this weekend and use extreme caution to avoid this
threat. Paddle smart from the start and always wear your life
jacket!

properties.headline: Special Marine Warning issued April 15 at 3:18AM EDT until April 15 at 4:15AM EDT by NWS Newport/Morehead City NC
properties.description:
The National Weather Service in Newport has issued a

* Special Marine Warning for...
Waters from Cape Hatteras to Ocracoke Inlet NC from 20 to 40 nm...
Waters from Oregon Inlet to Cape Hatteras NC from 20 to 40 nm...

* Until 415 AM EDT.

* At 317 AM EDT, a strong thunderstorm was located 19 nm southeast of
Monitor Marine Sanctuary, moving northeast at 25 knots.

HAZARD...Wind gusts 34 knots or greater and small hail.

SOURCE...Radar.

IMPACT...Small craft could be damaged in briefly higher winds and
suddenly higher waves.

* The strong thunderstorm will remain over mainly open waters.
properties.instruction:
Move to safe harbor until hazardous weather passes.

Frequent lightning is occurring with this storm. If caught on the
open water stay below deck if possible, keep away from ungrounded
metal objects.

properties.description:

* WHERE...Rush, Hodgeman, Pawnee, Haskell, Gray, Ford, Edwards,
Stevens, Seward and Meade Counties.

* WHEN...From 2 AM to 7 AM CDT Sunday.

* IMPACTS...Frost and freeze conditions will kill crops, other
sensitive vegetation and possibly damage unprotected outdoor
plumbing.
properties.instruction:

freezing and possible bursting of outdoor water pipes they should
be wrapped, drained, or allowed to drip slowly. Those that have
in-ground sprinkler systems should drain them and cover above-
ground pipes to protect them from freezing.

* WHERE...A portion of central North Carolina, including the
following county, Wake.

* WHEN...Until 345 AM EDT.

* IMPACTS...Flooding of rivers, creeks, streams, and other low-lying
and flood-prone locations is imminent or occurring. Streams
continue to rise due to excess runoff from earlier rainfall.

* ADDITIONAL DETAILS...
- At 1243 AM EDT, Automated rain gauges along Crabtree Creek
near Morrisville indicated continued rises due to heavy rain
from runoff of heavy rain from late Friday evening. Minor
flooding is ongoing or expected to begin shortly in the
advisory area.

Raleigh, Cary, Morrisville and William B Umstead State Park.
- http://www.weather.gov/safety/flood
properties.instruction:
Turn around, don't drown when encountering flooded roads. Most flood
deaths occur in vehicles.

dangers of flooding.

properties.description:

* HUMIDITY...Minimum humidity values from 10 to 15 percent during
the strongest winds.

* IMPACTS...any fires that develop will likely spread rapidly.
Outdoor burning is not recommended.
properties.instruction:
A Red Flag Warning means that critical fire weather conditions
are either occurring now, or will shortly. A combination of
strong winds, low relative humidity, and warm temperatures can
contribute to extreme fire behavior.

properties.headline: Flood Warning issued April 14 at 8:24PM MDT until April 18 at 8:55AM MDT by NWS Albuquerque NM
properties.description:
* WHAT...Minor flooding is forecast.

* WHERE...Jemez River above Jemez Pueblo.

* WHEN...Until Tuesday morning.

* IMPACTS...With a river stage between 7 and 8 feet, multiple
locations along highway 4 between San Ysidro and Jemez Springs
will see water crossing the road from tributaries and low water
crossing points. The Wastewater Treatment plant 1 mile downstream
of Jemez Springs can be impacted between 7 and 7.7 feet. Water
will be on Highway 4 at mile marker 1, 2 and 33. Homes near the
river in San Ysidro could also be impacted.

At a river flood stage of 8.0 feet, significant overbank flows will
occur from above Jemez Springs down through the Jemez Pueblo.
Further rises will result in bridges becoming unsafe to cross in and
around Jemez Springs.

At a river flood stage of 10.0 feet, widespread overbank flooding
will occur. Bridges in and around Jemez Springs will become either
impassable or unsafe to cross due to the high water and debris
caught up in the fast flow.

* ADDITIONAL DETAILS...
- At 7:45 PM MDT Friday the stage was 6.6 feet.
- Forecast...The river will oscillate around flood stage with a
maximum value of 8.3 feet Tuesday evening.
- Flood stage is 8.0 feet.
- Flood History...This crest compares to a previous crest of
8.2 feet on 08/24/1957.
- http://www.weather.gov/abq/EmergencyPrepFlood

properties.instruction:

deaths occur in vehicles.

enforcement and to the National Weather Service in Duluth when you
can do so safely. Flooding can be reported to the National Weather
Service at 1-800-685-8612.

properties.headline: Flood Advisory issued April 14 at 5:37PM MDT until April 16 at 6:00PM MDT by NWS Glasgow MT
properties.description:
* WHAT...Small stream flooding caused by snowmelt continues.

* WHERE...A portion of northeast Montana, including the following
counties, Daniels, Roosevelt, Sheridan and Valley.

* WHEN...Until 600 PM MDT Sunday.

* IMPACTS...Minor flooding in low-lying and poor drainage areas.
Rises in small streams and normally dry arroyos. Water over
roadways. Some low-water crossings may become impassable.

* ADDITIONAL DETAILS...
- At 537 PM MDT, local law enforcement reported snowmelt in the
advisory area. This is causing small stream flooding.
- http://www.weather.gov/safety/flood
properties.instruction:
Turn around, don't drown when encountering flooded roads. Most flood
deaths occur in vehicles.

Be especially cautious at night when it is harder to recognize the
dangers of flooding.

Please report observed flooding to local emergency services or law
enforcement and request they pass this information to the National
Weather Service when you can do so safely.

properties.headline: Flood Advisory issued April 14 at 3:14PM PDT until April 21 at 3:00PM PDT by NWS Reno NV
properties.description:
* WHAT...Flooding caused by upstream dam release and snowmelt is
occurring.

* WHERE...A portion of western Nevada along the East Walker River
below Bridgeport Reservoir, including the following county, Lyon.

* WHEN...Until further notice. Prolonged flooding is likely.

* IMPACTS...Flooding is expected to impact East Walker Road and
other low lying areas. River or stream flows are elevated.

* ADDITIONAL DETAILS...
- At 305 PM PDT, Flooding will result in the advisory area from
an upstream dam floodgate release combined with increased
snowmelt.
- Some locations that will experience flooding include...
mainly rural areas of Southern Lyon County, including East
Walker Road.
- http://www.weather.gov/safety/flood
properties.instruction:
Turn around, don't drown when encountering flooded roads. Most flood
deaths occur in vehicles.

NWSheadline: FLOOD ADVISORY FOR EAST WALKER RIVER IN LYON COUNTY IN EFFECT UNTIL FURTHER NOTICE

properties.headline: Flood Warning issued April 14 at 3:38PM CDT until April 17 at 5:00PM CDT by NWS Duluth MN
properties.description:
* WHAT...Flooding caused by snowmelt continues.

* WHERE...A portion of northwest Wisconsin, including the following
area, Douglas.

* WHEN...Until 500 PM CDT Monday.

* IMPACTS...Flooding on the Nemadji River.

* ADDITIONAL DETAILS...
- At 337 PM CDT, The Nemadji River will continue to slowly rise
as snow melt runoff makes its way into the river. At the gage
located at County Highway C, the river may approach a second
crest level of 25.5 feet today or Saturday and remain near
this level through the weekend.
- At a level of 23.5 feet, the water level is near the bottom
of the County Highway C Bridge. A large area of backwater
also forms upstream of the bridge at this level. Debris
jamming under the bridge is possible. At a level of 26 feet,
water encroaches a house west of the Nemadji River on County
Road C.
Rain this weekend will increase the rate of snowmelt. The
resulting runoff will cause water levels in area rivers to
rise and flooding is expected to continue.
- Some locations that will experience flooding include...
Locations along the Nemadji River in Douglas County.
- Flood safety information can be found at
www.weather.gov/safety/flood.
properties.instruction:
Turn around, don't drown when encountering flooded roads. Most flood
deaths occur in vehicles.

Keep children away from storm drains, culverts, creeks and streams.
Water levels can rise rapidly and sweep children away.

Stay away or be swept away. River banks and culverts can become
unstable and unsafe.

properties.description:
* WHAT...Flooding caused by snowmelt continues to be possible.

* WHERE...Portions of California and western Nevada, including the
following areas, in California, Greater Lake Tahoe Area,
Lassen-Eastern Plumas-Eastern Sierra Counties and Surprise Valley

Reno-Carson City-Minden Area and Mineral and Southern Lyon
Counties.

* WHEN...From Saturday afternoon through Monday morning.

* IMPACTS...Creeks and streams will be running high and fast.

participating in outdoor recreation this weekend should use
caution as water will be running high, fast, and potentially out
of banks for some creeks and streams. The water will be extremely
cold as well, quickly causing shock.

* ADDITIONAL DETAILS...
- http://www.weather.gov/safety/flood
properties.instruction:

Warnings. Those living in areas prone to flooding should be prepared
to take action should flooding develop.

properties.headline: Hydrologic Outlook issued April 14 at 1:41PM MDT by NWS Boise ID
properties.description:
Melting of the lower and mid elevation snowpack will increase
over the weekend as a warming trend occurs. This will increase
the risk of flooding along creeks, streams, and rivers this
weekend and early next week. The risk of sheet flooding in flat
low-lying terrain and poor drainage areas will increase as well.

If there is deep snow in your area, clear snow, ice and debris
from culverts and other flow paths to allow runoff to flow away
from buildings and other vulnerable infrastructure. Move deep snow
away from the foundations of buildings and move equipment, and
livestock out of poorly drained or low lying areas.

Stay tuned to the latest hydrologic forecasts.

NWSheadline: SNOWMELT WILL INCREASE THROUGH THE WEEKEND RESULTING IN RISING WATER LEVELS ON CREEKS, STREAMS, AND RIVERS

properties.headline: Hydrologic Outlook issued April 14 at 2:33PM CDT by NWS Grand Forks ND
properties.description:
Overland flooding may increase in coverage through this weekend
into next week across the Devils Lake Basin. A cooler pattern is
expected through this weekend, however daytime temperatures will
still rise above freezing allowing for additional melt to occur.
Temperatures begin to warm again next week accelerating the melt
of any lingering snowpack. If overland flooding occurs it may
eventually lead to impacts such as road closures, washouts, and
other snowmelt impacts.

Should a flood warning be issued for your area, see the warning
statement for information on how to prepare and mitigate flood-
related impacts.

If you have any questions, contact the NWS Grand Forks office at
701-772-0720.

You can follow us on the web at: weather.gov/fgf and on Facebook
at:
www.facebook.com/NWSGrandForks and on Twitter at: @NWSGrandForks.

properties.areaDesc: Dolores, CO; Montrose, CO; San Miguel, CO
properties.headline: Hydrologic Outlook issued April 14 at 1:07PM MDT by NWS Grand Junction CO
properties.description:
Snowmelt from record high snowpack in the Upper Dolores River Basin
has resulted in high flow along the Upper Dolores River. In
addition, rapid snowmelt has flooded multiple county roads across
Dolores, San Miguel and Montrose counties, which have impacted
access to the Dolores River.

Please visit Colorado BLM for updates on recent closures. Closure on
County Road 9.7 inhibits access, until further notice, to the
following BLM sites:

Mountain Sheep Point
Box Elder Recreation Site
Dolores River Canyon

Please avoid this area, as entering puts Search & Rescue crews at
risk!

High flow will continue this evening and overnight, until cooler
weather reduces the rate of snowmelt over the weekend.

properties.areaDesc: Lorain; Cuyahoga; Lake; Geauga; Ashtabula Inland; Medina; Summit; Portage; Ashtabula Lakeshore
properties.headline: Air Quality Alert issued April 14 at 3:07PM EDT by NWS Cleveland OH
properties.description:
An Air Quality Advisory for Ground Level Ozone has been issued by
the Northeast Ohio Areawide Coordinating Agency for Ashtabula,
Cuyahoga, Geauga, Lake, Lorain, Medina, Portage and Summit Counties.
The advisory is until midnight EDT Saturday night.

Air quality levels will be unhealthy for sensitive groups during
this period. If you are in the sensitive groups category of
children, the elderly and those with breathing difficulties, please
monitor your outdoor activity and check air quality readings at
airnow.gov. Additionally, sign-up at enviroflash.info for text
alerts regarding air quality.

To help our region reduce air pollution:

*Drive less: bike, walk, use transit, work from home, combine trips
*Visit gohiocommute.com/noaca - Find a smarter way to travel!
*Don't idle - Turn off your engine
*Refill your tank after sunset
*Wait to mow the lawn

* IMPACTS...Flooding of rivers, creeks, streams, and other low-lying
and flood-prone locations is imminent or occurring. Numerous roads
remain closed due to flooding.

* ADDITIONAL DETAILS...
- At 1240 PM CDT /1140 AM MDT/, Emergency management reported
flooding and multiple roads with water over in the north
central. In addition, the snowpack has been soaking into the
ground and the upper portions of soils are becoming
saturated. Areas that have appreciable snowpack remaining
will see additional runoff in the coming days as the ponding
water eventually makes its way through frozen culverts and
into the waterways. In the Prairie pothole region ponds and
sloughs may see water rise enough to run over roads.

become covered in water due to high water and plugged
culverts.

but towns and cities may also experience localized flooding
issues.

and flood-prone locations is imminent or occurring. Streams

the warned area. Flooding is already occurring.

cause water levels in
area rivers to increase and flooding is expected.

www.weather.gov/safety/flood.
properties.instruction:
Turn around, don't drown when encountering flooded roads. Most flood
deaths occur in vehicles.

unstable and unsafe.

enforcement and to the National Weather Service in Duluth when you
can do so safely. Flooding can be reported to the National Weather
Service at 1-800-685-8612.

railroad tracks. City of Hazen suffers little damage.

* ADDITIONAL DETAILS...
- At 8:00 AM CDT Friday the stage was 23.5 feet.
- Forecast...The river is expected to rise to a crest of 23.6
feet this afternoon.
- Flood stage is 21.0 feet.
- Flood History...This crest compares to a previous crest of
23.6 feet on 03/24/1948.

feet tonight.

NWSheadline: FLOOD WARNING FOR SNOWMELT REMAINS IN EFFECT UNTIL FURTHER NOTICE

properties.headline: Flood Warning issued April 14 at 8:54AM CDT until April 20 at 11:15AM CDT by NWS Grand Forks ND
properties.description:
* WHAT...Flooding caused by snowmelt continues.

* WHERE...A portion of northwest Minnesota, including the following
counties, Mahnomen and Norman.

* WHEN...Until 1115 AM CDT Thursday.

* IMPACTS...Flooding of rivers, creeks, streams, and other low-lying
and flood-prone locations is imminent or occurring.

* ADDITIONAL DETAILS...
- At 853 AM CDT, emergency management and the Minnesota
Department of Transportation reported of road closures and
water on roadways in Norman and Mahnomen County. Flooding is
expected to become more widespread as snowmelt continues.
properties.instruction:
Safety message - Turn around, don't drown. Don't travel through
flooded areas. Most flood deaths occur in vehicles.

Please report observed flooding to local emergency services or law
enforcement and request they pass this information to the National
Weather Service when you can do so safely.

NWSheadline: FLOOD WARNING FOR SNOWMELT REMAINS IN EFFECT UNTIL 1115 AM CDT THURSDAY

properties.areaDesc: Sussex; Warren; Morris; Hunterdon; Somerset; Middlesex; Western Monmouth; Eastern Monmouth; Mercer; Gloucester; Camden; Northwestern Burlington
properties.headline: Air Quality Alert issued April 14 at 9:14AM EDT by NWS Mount Holly NJ
properties.description:
The New Jersey Department of Environmental Protection has issued a
Air Quality Action Day for Ground Level Ozone, until 11 PM EDT this
evening.

An Ozone Action Day has been declared for Friday, April 14th, 2023.
Ozone has the potential to reach the unhealthy for sensitive groups
category for locations along the I-95 corridor. Sensitive individuals,
including the very young, the elderly, and persons with respiratory
diseases such as asthma, should avoid strenuous activities during the
afternoon and early evening hours.


For more information on current and forecast concentrations of
ground-level ozone and fine particulates, visit www.airnow.gov or
www.state.nj.us/dep/airmon/ .

properties.headline: Winter Weather Advisory issued April 14 at 3:25AM MDT until April 15 at 9:00AM MDT by NWS Denver CO
properties.description:
* WHAT...Snow expected, heavy at times this afternoon into this
evening. Total snow accumulations between 4 and 10 inches. Winds
gusting as high as 30 mph.

* WHERE...Rocky Mountain National Park and the Medicine Bow Range,
The Mountains of Summit County, the Mosquito Range, and the Indian
Peaks, the Front Range Foothills.

* WHEN...Until 9 AM MDT Saturday.

* IMPACTS...Snow covered roads will make travel hazardous,
especially through mountain passes. Use caution when traveling.
Difficult travel conditions are likely during the Friday evening
commute.
properties.instruction:
Slow down and use caution while traveling. The latest road
conditions for Colorado can be obtained by calling 5 1 1 or by going
to www.cotrip.org.

Chain and traction laws will possibly be enacted for the mountains.
If traveling to the mountains, be prepared for winter driving
conditions.

has declared Friday April 14th to be an Action Day for elevated
levels of ozone. Pollutants are expected to be in the unhealthy for
sensitive groups range.

The Action Day is in effect for the following Michigan counties...

Mason, Oceana, Muskegon, Ottawa, Kent, Allegan, and Van Buren

People and businesses are urged to avoid activities which lead
to ozone formation. These activities include refueling vehicles
or topping off when refueling, using gasoline powered lawn
equipment, and using charcoal lighter fluid. Positive activities
include car pooling, biking to work, delaying or combining
errands, and using water based paints.

It is recommended that active children and adults, and persons
with respiratory diseases such as asthma, limit prolonged
outdoor exertion.

For further information please see the Michigan Department of
Environment, Great Lakes, and Energy page on the internet at...
http://www.michigan.gov/EGLE.

properties.headline: Flood Warning issued April 13 at 7:00PM CDT until April 17 at 8:15PM CDT by NWS Aberdeen SD
properties.description:
* WHAT...Flooding caused by snowmelt continues.

* WHERE...A portion of northeast South Dakota, including the
following county, Day.

* WHEN...Until 815 PM CDT Monday.

* IMPACTS...Flooding of rivers, creeks, streams, roads, and other
low-lying and flood-prone locations is occurring. Numerous roads
remain closed due to flooding. Expect many areas of slow moving or
standing water.

* ADDITIONAL DETAILS...
- At 652 PM CDT, emergency management reported snowmelt
flooding continues in the warned area. Flooding of numerous
county and township roads continues including 447th Avenue,
south of Waubay.
- The office of Day County Emergency Management asks travelers
to exercise caution and obey posted road closure and detour
signs.
- Some locations that will experience flooding include...
Webster, Waubay, Bristol, Enemy Swim Housing, Roslyn,
Pierpont, Andover, Grenville, Butler, Lily, Holmquist,
Antelope Lake, Waubay Lake, Swan Lake, Minnewasta Lake, Rush
Lake, Opitz Lake, Waubay Wildlife Rec Area, Bitter Lake and
Blue Dog Lake.
- http://www.weather.gov/safety/flood
properties.instruction:
Turn around, don't drown when encountering flooded roads. Most flood
deaths occur in vehicles.

Be especially cautious at night when it is harder to recognize the
dangers of flooding.

In hilly terrain there are hundreds of low water crossings which are
potentially dangerous in heavy rain. Do not attempt to cross flooded
roads. Find an alternate route.

Please report observed flooding to local emergency services or law
enforcement and request they pass this information to the National
Weather Service when you can do so safely.

properties.headline: Flood Warning issued April 13 at 6:18PM CDT until April 20 at 7:00AM CDT by NWS Twin Cities/Chanhassen MN
properties.description:
* WHAT...Minor flooding is forecast.

* WHERE...Sauk River at St. Cloud.

* WHEN...Until Thursday morning.

* IMPACTS...At 6.0 feet, Very low roadways may be impacted from
Richmond to St. Cloud; water reaching foundations of a few homes.

* ADDITIONAL DETAILS...
- At 515 PM CDT Thursday, the stage was 5.9 feet.
- Forecast...The river is expected to rise above flood stage
late this evening to a crest of 6.2 feet early Saturday
morning. It will then fall below flood stage Wednesday
morning.
- Flood stage is 6.0 feet.
- Flood History...This crest compares to a previous crest of
6.2 feet on 03/27/1957.

NWSheadline: FLOOD WARNING FOR SNOWMELT IN EFFECT UNTIL THURSDAY MORNING

properties.headline: Flood Warning issued April 13 at 4:00PM MDT until April 15 at 12:00PM MDT by NWS Grand Junction CO
properties.description:
* WHAT...Flooding caused by snowmelt is occurring.

* WHERE...A portion of northwest Colorado, within Routt County,
including the town of Hayden.

* WHEN...Until noon MDT Saturday.

* IMPACTS...Flooding of rivers, creeks, streams, and other low-lying
and flood-prone locations is imminent or occurring. Low-water
crossings may be inundated with water and potentially impassable.

* ADDITIONAL DETAILS...
- At 357 PM MDT, local law enforcement reported flooding in the
warned area.
- Some locations that will experience flooding include...
Hayden along Highway 40.
- http://www.weather.gov/safety/flood
properties.instruction:
Turn around, don't drown when encountering flooded roads. Most flood
deaths occur in vehicles.

Please report observed flooding to local emergency services or law
enforcement and request they pass this information to the National
Weather Service when you can do so safely.

NWSheadline: FLOOD WARNING FOR SNOWMELT IN EFFECT UNTIL NOON MDT SATURDAY

properties.areaDesc: Tusas Mountains Including Chama; Jemez Mountains; Glorieta Mesa Including Glorieta Pass; Northern Sangre de Cristo Mountains; Southern Sangre de Cristo Mountains; East Slopes Sangre de Cristo Mountains; Upper Rio Grande Valley; Espanola Valley
properties.headline: Special Weather Statement issued April 13 at 3:57PM MDT by NWS Albuquerque NM
properties.description:
Warm temperatures over northern mountain snowpack are driving
rapid runoff. Creeks and rivers in the mountains will experience
rapid rises. Mountain roads may experience localized flooding.


HAZARD...Rising creeks and rivers. Possible localized flooding.

IMPACT...Potential for impassable roads at high elevations.

Locations impacted include...
All rivers and creeks in the Sangre de Cristo and Tusas mountains.
All northern tributaries of the Rio Grande.
properties.instruction:
Exercise extreme caution near cold fast flowing water. Do not
drive through flooded roadways. Be wary of rock and mudslides in
steep locations.

NWSheadline: RAPID SNOWMELT LEADING TO EXCESSIVE RUNOFF IN NORTHERN MOUNTAINS OF NEW MEXICO

properties.headline: Flood Warning issued April 13 at 3:51PM MDT until April 15 at 12:00PM MDT by NWS Grand Junction CO
properties.description:
* WHAT...Flooding caused by snowmelt is expected.

* WHERE...A portion of east central Utah, within Grand County, along
the Dolores River from the UT/CO stateline to the confluence with
the Colorado River.

* WHEN...Until noon MDT Saturday.

* IMPACTS...Flooding of rivers, creeks, streams, and other low-lying
and flood-prone locations is imminent or occurring. Streams
continue to rise due to excess runoff from snowmelt. Low-water
crossings may be inundated with water and may not be passable.

* ADDITIONAL DETAILS...
- At 344 PM MDT, gage reports indicated the potential for
accelerated flow due to recent snowmelt. Flooding is expected
to begin this evening in the warned area.
- This includes portions of the following streams and
drainages...
Fisher Creek, Waring Canyon, Beaver Creek, Dolores River and
Granite Creek.
- Some locations that will experience flooding include...
mainly rural areas of Southeastern Grand County
- http://www.weather.gov/safety/flood
properties.instruction:
Turn around, don't drown when encountering flooded roads. Most flood
deaths occur in vehicles. Do not attempt to cross flooded roads.
Find an alternate route.

Please report observed flooding to local emergency services or law
enforcement and request they pass this information to the National
Weather Service when you can do so safely.

NWSheadline: FLOOD WARNING FOR SNOWMELT IN EFFECT UNTIL NOON MDT SATURDAY

properties.headline: Flood Warning issued April 13 at 3:45PM CDT until April 19 at 8:30PM CDT by NWS Milwaukee/Sullivan WI
properties.description:
* WHAT...Minor flooding is occurring and minor flooding is forecast.

* WHERE...Wisconsin River at Portage.

* WHEN...Until Wednesday evening.

* IMPACTS...At 18.0 feet, Water surrounds seasonal homes along Old
River Rd in the Blackhawk Park and 12 homes flooded on Hwy V. Old
River Rd covered with water. West Lane Rd in the Long Lake area
has 4 feet of water over it in places. Water over River Oaks Rd
near Hwy V and Oak Knoll Rd in Town of Dekorra 7 miles downstream.
Water at base of Caledonia/Lewiston Levee on Old River Rd. This
level is about a 20 percent chance flood meaning that there is a
20 percent chance in any given year of the river reaching this
level.

* ADDITIONAL DETAILS...
- At 3:30 PM CDT Thursday the stage was 17.9 feet.
- Bankfull stage is 12.7 feet.
- Recent Activity...The maximum river stage in the 24 hours
ending at 3:30 PM CDT Thursday was 17.9 feet.
- Forecast...The river is expected to fall below flood stage
early Wednesday afternoon and continue falling to 16.1 feet
Thursday morning.
- Flood stage is 17.0 feet.
- Flood History...This crest compares to a previous crest of
17.9 feet on 04/20/2003.
- http://www.weather.gov/safety/flood

NWSheadline: FLOOD WARNING REMAINS IN EFFECT UNTIL WEDNESDAY EVENING

properties.areaDesc: Cook, MN; Itasca, MN; Koochiching, MN; Lake, MN; St. Louis, MN
properties.headline: Flood Advisory issued April 13 at 3:43PM CDT until April 17 at 4:00PM CDT by NWS Duluth MN
properties.description:
* WHAT...Flooding caused by snowmelt is expected.

* WHERE...Portions of north central Minnesota and northeast
Minnesota, including the following areas, in north central
Minnesota, Itasca and Koochiching. In northeast Minnesota, Cook,
Lake and St. Louis.

* WHEN...Until 400 PM CDT Monday.

* IMPACTS...Minor flooding in low-lying and poor drainage areas.
Overflowing poor drainage areas. Ponding of water in urban or
other areas is occurring or is imminent.

* ADDITIONAL DETAILS...
- At 338 PM CDT, gauge reports and forest service officials
indicated snowmelt. Overflowing poor drainage areas will
cause minor flooding in the advisory area.
- Forest service reported ponding of water in ditches and along
the edge of roads. Water was leading to washouts along forest
roads in the Tofte and Gunflint Ranger districts as of
Thursday afternoon.
- Some locations that will experience flooding include...
Hibbing, International Falls, Ely, Grand Marais, Lake
Vermilion, Gunflint Lake, Virginia, Chisholm, Two Harbors,
Eveleth, Mountain Iron, Hoyt Lakes, Silver Bay, Gilbert,
Aurora, Babbitt, Keewatin, Buhl, Nashwauk and Biwabik.
- Flood safety information can be found at
www.weather.gov/safety/flood.
properties.instruction:
Turn around, don't drown when encountering flooded roads. Most flood
deaths occur in vehicles.

Be especially cautious at night when it is harder to recognize the
dangers of flooding.

Report observed flooding to local emergency services or law
enforcement and to the National Weather Service in Duluth when you
can do so safely. Flooding can be reported to the National Weather
Service at 1-800-685-8612.

* WHEN...Until Friday, April 21.

that time. The rough location of Road 50 and Big Sandy Creek is
about 7 miles north of the casino on Highway 87, then go 3 miles
west.

* ADDITIONAL DETAILS...

feet this afternoon. It will then slowly fall to below flood

properties.headline: Hydrologic Outlook issued April 13 at 5:08AM CDT by NWS Green Bay WI
properties.description:
The unseasonably warm airmass will remain in the Great Lakes through
Saturday, resulting in daytime temperatures climbing to 15 to 30
degrees above normal. Snow water equivalent values are anomalously
high across far northern Wisconsin and Upper Michigan. Excessive
snowmelt will continue, with most or all of the snow having melted
by this weekend. There also remains a lot of water to push through
the rivers across central Wisconsin and in/west of the Fox Valley.

Minor to possibly moderate flooding is expected to continue along
streams, rivers, and other low-lying areas that regularly experience
spring snowmelt flooding. Flows will continue to increase as well,
especially on the Menominee.

Additional precipitation Saturday into early next week may bring
new and/or continue/enhance ongoing flooding concerns for area
rivers.

If you live in or commute through an area that has previously
experienced spring melt flooding, prepare for potential impacts.

The next update to this outlook is expected by 8:00 AM CDT
Saturday April, 15, 2023.

expected in the surf zone.

Counties. In Florida, Escambia Coastal, Santa Rosa Coastal and
Okaloosa Coastal Counties.

* WHEN...For the High Rip Current Risk, through late Friday
night. For the High Surf Advisory, from 7 AM Wednesday to 1 PM
CDT Thursday.

localized beach erosion. Rip currents can sweep even the best
swimmers away from shore into deeper water.
properties.instruction:
Inexperienced swimmers should remain out of the water due to
dangerous surf conditions.

Swim near a lifeguard. If caught in a rip current, relax and
float. Don't swim against the current. If able, swim in a
direction following the shoreline. If unable to escape, face the
shore and call or wave for help.

properties.areaDesc: Mobile Coastal; Baldwin Coastal; Escambia Coastal; Santa Rosa Coastal; Okaloosa Coastal
properties.headline: Rip Current Statement issued April 10 at 8:40AM CDT until April 15 at 6:00AM CDT by NWS Mobile AL
properties.description:
* WHAT...Dangerous rip currents.

* WHERE...In Alabama, Mobile Coastal and Baldwin Coastal
Counties. In Florida, Escambia Coastal, Santa Rosa Coastal and
Okaloosa Coastal Counties.

* WHEN...Through late Friday night.

* IMPACTS...Rip currents can sweep even the best swimmers away
from shore into deeper water.
properties.instruction:
Swim near a lifeguard. If caught in a rip current, relax and
float. Don't swim against the current. If able, swim in a
direction following the shoreline. If unable to escape, face the
shore and call or wave for help.
